how I stopped worrying about hiring, because this is something as the team is growing,

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:05.520
you start getting to these concerns about how do you scale the applications and how

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:13.399
do you scale your team to work across one or many different applications? So as a getting

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:18.480
good presentation, we're going to summarize this as a graph. And so there's always this

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:23.679
trade-off that we have in our work as data scientists or software developers between

00:04:23.679 --> 00:04:29.320
complexity and what I just call being hackish in terms of trying to implement something.

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:33.959
And we probably have all felt it. We're working on trying to do something that's more complex,

00:04:33.959 --> 00:04:40.119
but we're trying to do it without hacking around, being too clever on trying to implement

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:44.760
a solution, trying to back in engineering something to make it work, because that creates

00:04:44.799 --> 00:04:50.880
long-term liability. You might be the only person that knows how to deal with a particular

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:57.079
solution that you've built. So in that upper left-hand quadrant there, you see that sort

00:04:57.079 --> 00:05:01.959
of programmer's lure where you do a lot of complexity, but you don't do it in a very

00:05:01.959 --> 00:05:07.679
hackish way. In the lower right-hand corner, that Rube Goldberg zone of doing something

00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:12.200
that's not very complex, but doing it in an absolute hackish way. And that 45-degree line

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:17.959
is really that balance and trying to recognize, okay, how do we do more complex things again

00:05:17.959 --> 00:05:23.040
without being too hackish on the solution? And this is something that Bijan and I and

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:27.559
our team think about quite a bit. How do we do our work well is essentially what this

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:34.720
summarizes to. So we're going to talk about how microservices helps you do things with

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:42.839
greater complexity or complex needs, but without going into too much of a hackish zone.

00:05:42.839 --> 00:05:49.600
So this is something that we often see within growing our analytics tool set. So as you

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:53.880
see in those big bubbles, we talk about the progression of user needs over time. So when

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:59.480
you build a data science application or some sort of solution, you know, immediately you

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:03.160
make folks happy. You make your data scientists happy. You make your developers happy because

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:08.480
you say, hey, somebody needed something. I got a version one out there. Everybody's fantastic

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:14.720
and everybody's happy. And then the user needs increase. And sometimes that's just, okay,

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:21.000
need a few more graphs. Okay. There's more complexity, more interactivity that's needed.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.359
There's other things that need to be polished, nicer looking buttons. Then there's things

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:29.640
that start to kind of grate at you. Like, well, I really like these graphs. Can you

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:35.079
have them so they can be exported into PowerPoint? Like, okay, we can. Don't want to do that,

00:06:35.079 --> 00:06:40.200
but sure. If that's what you needed. And then after you get all that done, a user might

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:43.359
come back to you. He's like, actually, no, my priorities were different. I need something

00:06:43.359 --> 00:06:47.160
completely different. And that's, this is that progression where you're trying to balance

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:52.839
with your data scientists on their happiness and your developer team's happiness. So they

00:06:52.839 --> 00:06:57.880
can be engaged. They continue to get that satisfaction working in projects and try to

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:03.959
avoid some of that grading aspects on progressing and changing your applications and solutions

00:07:03.959 --> 00:07:10.799
over a period of time. And when you do this in Shiny, there's a number of different issues

00:07:10.799 --> 00:07:17.320
that pop up. One of which really is it becomes more and more difficult to have multiple developers

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:22.959
on working on the same piece of code. Because the way the Shiny applications and the application

00:07:22.959 --> 00:07:27.320
structure tends to work, you tend to work on one or two individual files. Now there's

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:32.200
workarounds to this. Certainly you can source other files, you can do other tricks, but

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:37.100
it gets complicated over a period of time. So you might having two coders who are trying

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:42.200
to work on the same segments of code, somebody who's working on a very large segment of code,

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:48.359
other people might be waiting on that other segment of code to be done. And there's oftentimes

00:07:48.359 --> 00:07:53.959
this conflicts that start to arise. And we're going to talk about a project today that was

00:07:53.959 --> 00:08:01.320
getting to 15,000 lines of code in Shiny. And it was creating a large number of conflicts

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:07.440
as the development team was trying to work on new features.

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:12.679
So it has led us to microservices. If we take a look at those different challenges and those

00:08:12.679 --> 00:08:16.839
balancing needs, we want to start talking about microservices. So we're going to describe

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:20.480
this at a high level and then we're going to dive into it quite a bit. And I will say

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:25.600
there will be a forthcoming blog post that dives into the technical details a lot more.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:31.519
So we're going to address this at a cursory level for a period of time. So in short, this

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:37.159
is a very short version of it. Microservices really help separate out the different layers

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:43.400
of an application. So there can be a web or user interface that allows somebody to navigate

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:48.320
information, but that's separate from the underlying logic of the application. Or in

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:53.599
the case of Shiny, those things get mashed together into a same or what we call a monolithic

00:08:53.599 --> 00:08:58.799
code structure because it separates it out because underneath that interface, you have

00:08:58.799 --> 00:09:05.320
a series of APIs or web services, RESTful APIs, things like that, that allow you to

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:10.719
build APIs that control that interactivity. So when somebody is clicking on something

00:09:10.719 --> 00:09:16.679
in a web browser, it's communicating via APIs behind it. And behind those APIs is a data

00:09:16.679 --> 00:09:24.559
storage or database technology that allows you to query and bring in data. And that separation

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:30.599
between the user interface and APIs and web services helps simplify your code structure

00:09:30.599 --> 00:09:35.440
and also allows different people to work on the same bits of code. And the reason why

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:41.200
we're talking about this here today is because that web interface and those APIs and web

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:48.840
services can be completely hosted on RStudio Connect. RStudio Connect basically is a web

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:55.080
server and you can host web files on there. If you upload index.html, it will render that

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:59.919
in addition to Shiny and everything else. So it allows us to host things such as a React

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:04.840
or Angular or other web technology within the RStudio Connect environment. And for us,

00:10:04.840 --> 00:10:10.719
we use the React technology. And again, that's hosted on top of APIs and web services, which

00:10:10.719 --> 00:10:15.640
could be done in either Plumber, which we have done in our team, or using Flask in the

00:10:15.640 --> 00:10:22.919
Python language. So what is a simple example of a microservices look like? Let's say we

00:10:22.919 --> 00:10:26.840
have a bunch of time series data and we want to do a forecast of that time series data.

00:10:26.840 --> 00:10:30.599
And you're actually going to see a demo of this here in a moment. But to explain the

00:10:30.599 --> 00:10:35.679
architecture, you have data that's holding on to historical time series information.

00:10:35.679 --> 00:10:41.719
So all those entries about historical entries for the time series. Then you have a model.

00:10:41.719 --> 00:10:49.159
Let's say it's an ARIMA model that can do the forecasting that is written by data scientists.

00:10:49.159 --> 00:10:54.280
And then on top of that, you deploy APIs and web services that communicate back to that

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:59.280
analytical model, that in turn communicate back to that database, that will actually

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:05.799
do the forecast. And then that forecasted data is then presented up to the website or

00:11:05.799 --> 00:11:12.640
the dashboard that allows the user to see that in a visual format. And so the reason

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:18.039
why we separate that apart is because then the front end, that user interface, can be

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:22.119
developed by an independent web developer or a full stack developer. And you can have

00:11:22.119 --> 00:11:26.640
web designers working on that. So you don't need to hire that shiny developer anymore

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:32.400
and focus on that very particular skill set, but be able to bring in web development technologies

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:37.520
that are more broadly used in other environments as well. Meanwhile, the web services can be

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:41.559
programmed by your data scientists because it can be done in R, the Python language,

00:11:41.559 --> 00:11:46.239
in addition to the data engineer or backend developer or other full stack developers to

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:50.559
be able to build out those web services. And then again, this is in contrast to a shiny

00:11:50.559 --> 00:11:55.320
application architecture where really that front end and all that logic a lot of times

00:11:55.320 --> 00:12:00.520
is buried in the shiny piece of the application. And so that restricts the number of individuals

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:05.960
who really can do work on that piece. And the takeaway of why this is so beneficial,

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:10.919
it really allows that front end development technology to flourish because you can tap

00:12:10.919 --> 00:12:17.520
into the entire ecosystem of development technologies that can be brought to bear with your web

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:24.200
developers. So I talked about a time series example. And so it'd be great to then share

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:27.679
an example, actually take a look at a code base of what does that look like? What does

00:12:27.679 --> 00:12:34.159
Microsoft services look like within an application using a very simple hello world example? And

00:12:34.159 --> 00:12:37.000
for that, Bijan is okay if I turn it over to you.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:44.520
Absolutely. Yeah, I will take it on from here. Like Tom mentioned, this is a very simple

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:49.960
demonstration of a microservice that would do some prediction. I'll get into a little

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:58.440
bit of the details of the back end in a second. But this took not more than a day to put together.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:02.679
The front end is in a React application and the back end is hosted on RStudio Connect

00:13:02.679 --> 00:13:07.840
using Plumber. This demonstration is pretty simple. A user would come in, they would say,

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:15.039
I want to see a forecast of some time series data over the next 48 periods. We'd hit submit.

00:13:15.039 --> 00:13:22.280
What's happening now is the client side is making a request to RStudio Connect to our API.

00:13:22.280 --> 00:13:25.799
It's making that prediction with our pre-trained model, and then it's responding with all of

00:13:25.799 --> 00:13:31.760
that information. The benefit of having those two separate, as opposed to having Shiny kind

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:36.119
of handle it all at once, is that Shiny has to render the front end and do the computation

00:13:36.119 --> 00:13:40.880
on the back end. That's fine for one person. But when you try to scale things, that puts

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:46.400
a lot of load on the server. Having this separation lets the client side do some light

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:53.400
calculations and rendering, and then the heavier calculations on the back end. Again, very

00:13:53.400 --> 00:14:00.200
simple demonstration of what microservices can do. One thing that I want to also kind

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:04.719
of call out here is that one of the benefits of having them separate like this is that

00:14:04.719 --> 00:14:07.719
you can actually touch the back end without the front end.

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:13.239
Just a quick question, Bijan, if you could zoom in a little bit when you flip over to the other one.

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:20.200
Awesome, thank you.

00:14:21.799 --> 00:14:29.799
I'm not sure if I can zoom in on this one. I'll just speak to it briefly. I'll get into a

00:14:29.799 --> 00:14:33.200
little bit more on the testing, which is what is using Postman, which is what I'm showing

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:38.440
here. But one benefit of a microservice back end is that you can touch those back end points

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:44.239
without having to go through a web interface. So one thing that I just did is I made a

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:49.599
prediction, but that prediction service is actually calling another service that does our

00:14:49.599 --> 00:14:55.520
logging. So I can also make a request and see, OK, well, I just made a request two minutes

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:57.599
ago for a prediction.

00:14:59.119 --> 00:15:04.359
Just being able to touch the back end from different systems is a huge benefit for

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:08.880
microservices because you don't have everything encapsulated into one code base.

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:13.960
So what I'm showing here is the architecture of that relatively basic

00:15:15.919 --> 00:15:24.440
microservice app. So we saw the web interface, which is a React based application, and I made a

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:28.280
request to one microservice, one service that does our forecast.

00:15:29.239 --> 00:15:33.119
That service also made a request to a separate service that handles all of our logging.

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:40.080
This may not, it may not make sense to, you know, why do you have these two separate until you

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:44.760
start thinking about when you start building other products, you probably don't want to use the

00:15:44.760 --> 00:15:50.159
same logging service. So you get that benefit of not having to build in every single app and

00:15:50.200 --> 00:15:55.400
instead call to the one instance that you have from every single one of your apps.

00:15:56.359 --> 00:16:01.919
One example I can give you is about a year ago, we had a fundamental change to our logging

00:16:01.919 --> 00:16:04.880
code where we were using a package at the time.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:10.640
Every single one of our Shiny apps, which was roughly about 20 of them, had that code

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:14.039
installed when they when they were published to RStudio Connect.

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:18.400
When we had to make that change, we actually had to have all of our developers pause their

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:24.000
work, spend about two weeks making that change in their code, testing out their code, and

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.880
then republishing their applications, every single one of them.

00:16:27.679 --> 00:16:32.840
Had we had a micro logging service, it would have been as simple as changing the one

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:37.080
service, doing the testing as well, but it would be substantially less work.

00:16:38.599 --> 00:16:44.799
So that's the reason for the separation and a good reason why you'd want to to separate those

00:16:44.799 --> 00:16:46.799
duties instead of having it all on one code base.

00:16:47.799 --> 00:16:53.440
And then the database is very similar to Shiny, you would have some sort of storage that you

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:58.840
don't have your your app save data or put it on a file system or something like that.

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:10.079
So now I'll get into a bit of the lessons learned that we came across while transitioning

00:17:10.079 --> 00:17:11.800
over to a microservice architecture.

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:18.000
About a year, year and a half ago, we started the first application on this this type of

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:23.920
architecture. So we were moving from a monolithic Shiny application, as Tom mentioned

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:27.359
before, it was the application that grew to about 15,000 lines of code.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:34.400
There were some challenges with the monolithic architecture that that more or less pushed us

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:37.640
into making a decision of do we do we make the switch now?

00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:40.239
So a year and a half ago, we started that switch.

00:17:40.479 --> 00:17:46.439
And the intent of this part of the presentation is to talk through some challenges that we ran

00:17:46.439 --> 00:17:48.280
into and how we overcame them.

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:56.439
So there are four pretty overarching challenges with getting started with microservices, and

00:17:56.439 --> 00:18:00.400
the first one is getting started with microservices can be very daunting.

00:18:00.719 --> 00:18:02.199
There's a lot of material out there.

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:09.839
Microservices are defined very similarly, but slightly different depending on which source you

00:18:09.839 --> 00:18:15.760
look at. And on top of that, planning for your application is really a very open ended

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:22.199
problem because you're thinking of a service that could potentially be reused and a future

00:18:22.199 --> 00:18:23.719
use case that you have no idea about.

00:18:25.119 --> 00:18:29.119
And so what you want to do is you want to plan for that service that's general enough to

00:18:29.239 --> 00:18:34.599
where it could be applied in the future and you wouldn't have to change the interface at that

00:18:34.599 --> 00:18:38.800
point in time, but not too general to where you're trying to build for the world.

00:18:40.319 --> 00:18:49.040
On top of that, because these services can be used with different user interfaces, it

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:54.839
becomes a lot more important to define what that interface is, because if you do have to

00:18:54.839 --> 00:18:58.640
change it in the future, you have to go back and you have to test all the older versions or

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:00.199
handle version control very carefully.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:05.920
So getting started is quite a challenge and we'll talk to that a bit here.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:13.000
Separation of developer duties comes with a lot of benefits because you can hire for

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:19.479
specialized skill sets, but at the same time, coordination amongst your team is even more

00:19:19.479 --> 00:19:20.920
important in that case.

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:26.400
The application that we built over the last year and a half was actually a worldwide team

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:28.599
from literally all parts of the world.

00:19:28.599 --> 00:19:33.000
We had maybe a two hour window of everybody being online at the same time.

00:19:34.719 --> 00:19:40.079
And so we'll get into a little bit of how we overcame that challenge in a second as well.

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:49.119
The third thing here is that microservices are great for scaling things out, but they do

00:19:49.119 --> 00:19:54.000
come with their own set of risks that monolithic apps don't necessarily have.

00:19:54.719 --> 00:19:56.760
I'll talk a little bit more about that in a second.

00:19:57.479 --> 00:20:03.839
And then finally, the whole microservice architecture, it generally as a data scientist,

00:20:03.839 --> 00:20:05.239
there was a big knowledge gap there.

00:20:06.839 --> 00:20:11.920
The way to kind of address that is to attend meetups like this and later take a look at our

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:13.839
blog posts, but do your own research as well.

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:19.040
Data scientists traditionally may or may not know a lot about design patterns or HTTP

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:22.800
requests. So there's generally some knowledge gaps.

00:20:23.239 --> 00:20:28.839
On top of that, smaller teams and smaller projects may not get as much of a benefit out of

00:20:28.839 --> 00:20:34.760
switching to a microservice architecture versus a monolithic app, just purely based on the

00:20:34.760 --> 00:20:39.119
fact that microservices may take a bit more upfront cost.

00:20:39.599 --> 00:20:43.760
And if you're not planning on reusing those services or have no intent to ever reuse those

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:46.479
services, it may be cost that you don't necessarily want to take on.

00:20:47.359 --> 00:20:49.520
So that's a fourth challenge.

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:52.760
The cost benefit of it is something to always consider.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:57.479
So how do you address getting started?

00:20:58.959 --> 00:21:04.199
So one thing that we started with is using domain driven design.

00:21:04.479 --> 00:21:07.959
If you search microservices, this is very commonly what pops up first.

00:21:08.880 --> 00:21:12.439
Domain driven design is using the business domain.

00:21:12.439 --> 00:21:16.479
So knowledge about the business to conceptualize what you actually need to be building.

00:21:17.239 --> 00:21:21.280
And then you take that and you build those as entities in your system.

00:21:22.079 --> 00:21:23.520
So I've listed some steps here.

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:27.280
The first thing is that you want to identify your entities in your business domain.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:32.640
In this graphic at the bottom left here, I've just put up a simple kind of e-commerce sort of

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:36.920
thing. So you have customers who are their own entity, you have products that are their own

00:21:36.920 --> 00:21:39.640
entity, and you have orders that are also an entity.

00:21:41.119 --> 00:21:44.439
Those are three entities in a very simple system or a very simple business.

00:21:46.199 --> 00:21:49.680
The second step would be understand how those entities relate to each other.

00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:53.680
So customers will search for products, they'll make orders, orders will have products.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:58.400
Relatively simple relationship.

00:21:58.439 --> 00:22:04.599
But the point of these two parts is to then get to this third part of what services do you

00:22:04.599 --> 00:22:07.760
need to do? What actions do you need to take on these entities?

00:22:08.319 --> 00:22:14.800
So on the right hand side here, for each one of the entities that I have, I have user

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:19.400
HTTP API verbs.

00:22:21.400 --> 00:22:27.119
So you get a sense of, OK, for a customer, I need to be able to get the list of customers.

00:22:27.160 --> 00:22:28.719
I need to be able to create customers.

00:22:28.719 --> 00:22:30.160
I need to be able to edit customers.

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:31.839
I may need to remove customers.

00:22:32.479 --> 00:22:36.839
And so that defines the endpoints that you individually would need to create.

00:22:37.239 --> 00:22:40.079
And those endpoints create that service for customers.

00:22:41.079 --> 00:22:45.839
Similarly, on products, you may not need to be able to edit, which is the put request or delete.

00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:49.839
And so you may have a little bit less work for products.

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:54.800
But again, you create that service for products and then similarly for orders.

00:22:56.839 --> 00:23:03.599
The key point for this slide is that following these three steps gets you from this kind of

00:23:03.599 --> 00:23:07.560
wide open field to these are what I need to be focusing on.

00:23:07.599 --> 00:23:10.800
There may be things around them, but these are the things that you need to be focusing on.

00:23:12.920 --> 00:23:17.760
Now, going into the second part of planning, which is applying design patterns and

00:23:17.760 --> 00:23:19.280
specifically cloud design patterns.

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:24.599
So I mentioned that these entities in these relationships define the kind of areas that you need to

00:23:24.599 --> 00:23:27.680
focus on, but there are things around them that may pop up as well.

00:23:28.239 --> 00:23:30.079
That's what design patterns help you identify.

00:23:30.079 --> 00:23:34.079
So there's plenty of material out there as well on design patterns.

00:23:34.319 --> 00:23:41.479
But three that we've used are known as sidecar patterns, anti-corruption layers and backends for frontends.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:47.920
What these do is they categorize your services that may not necessarily apply to products, for example,

00:23:48.560 --> 00:23:55.800
but may serve a very particular frontend that needs to know what the list of products or have

00:23:55.800 --> 00:23:57.479
products formatted in a very certain way.

00:23:58.199 --> 00:24:01.680
You can write a service that services that frontend specifically.

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:08.400
Very commonly, we have websites that are designed for web and mobile, and they unfortunately have some

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:14.760
differences. Being able to write a service that supports each one or handles one versus the other helps you

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.760
kind of abstract that out of having one service handle too many things.

00:24:20.239 --> 00:24:24.119
Similarly, sidecars are things like the logging service that I pointed to earlier.

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:30.439
There are things that your application or your client will never touch, but there are things that

00:24:30.520 --> 00:24:36.599
your backend architecture will touch or things that are used behind the scenes that are never seen by the user.

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:40.400
The third one here is anti-corruption layers.

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:48.239
I bring this up because while we were switching over from a monolithic app to a microservices app, there was a

00:24:48.239 --> 00:24:49.479
transition we had to take.

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:55.239
We had a legacy system that we had to interface with our newer application.

00:24:55.640 --> 00:24:57.520
Anti-corruption layers are designed for that.

00:24:57.839 --> 00:25:05.479
The intent here is that you serve from the legacy system to your new application, but you don't have to

00:25:05.479 --> 00:25:08.479
include that kind of information inside of your app services.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:16.800
The idea of microservices, starting with micro, is that you have them very specialized, doing one thing very

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:22.760
well, but have logical separation to where one service is not stepping over another service.

00:25:27.800 --> 00:25:31.719
The next part here is separation of development duties.

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:35.439
I'll just go into a bit of what we did.

00:25:35.640 --> 00:25:45.239
We defined a very structured documentation format for every one of our endpoints or every one of our

00:25:45.239 --> 00:25:50.520
services, and we also utilize Slider pretty heavily.

00:25:50.640 --> 00:26:00.640
So a lot of these details will be coming in the blog in the future, but to go at a high level, every single

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:07.199
endpoint that we built that comprises a service started with documentation, this exact documentation on the

00:26:07.199 --> 00:26:07.760
right here.

00:26:08.359 --> 00:26:13.520
And the intent was to have front-end, back-end, every developer on the team be on the same page and know

00:26:13.520 --> 00:26:16.359
exactly what is going to be the interface.

00:26:17.359 --> 00:26:21.520
Like I mentioned before, if you change the interface, everybody else has to change the work that they're

00:26:21.520 --> 00:26:23.040
doing if they're touching that.

00:26:23.439 --> 00:26:27.920
And so establishing that up front was crucial for us to be effective.

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:35.239
We found that this kind of format helps in a lot of ways because we define what's required, both in a request

00:26:35.239 --> 00:26:38.880
and a response, or what comes back in your response, as well as types.

00:26:40.359 --> 00:26:43.239
And an example generally helps go a long way.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:48.760
On top of that, one of the great things about Plumber is that it builds your Swagger documentation

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:49.479
automatically.

00:26:50.359 --> 00:26:57.400
And so while you're building your microservice, you can kind of validate what you're building, or anybody

00:26:57.400 --> 00:27:00.959
can validate on the team what you're building, against the documentation.

00:27:01.199 --> 00:27:07.239
They just simply have to go to the URL on RStudio Connect and click on the right endpoint.

00:27:08.199 --> 00:27:15.160
Okay, so the third part here is talking about how to manage the newer risk that comes with microservices.

00:27:16.079 --> 00:27:20.079
So one of the big risks of microservices is that they can be distributed.

00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:26.400
A monolithic architecture is generally one virtual machine or one machine that's running everything.

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:32.640
So all the calculations for the back end and for the front end are all from the single node.

00:27:33.479 --> 00:27:39.400
A microservice could be on a Lambda function, it could be on another virtual machine, it could even be

00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:40.359
external to your company.

00:27:40.359 --> 00:27:45.640
It could be using a third-party API that serves for a certain reason.

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:51.439
All of those come with risks because every degree of freedom you give to your system will introduce a

00:27:51.439 --> 00:27:53.719
potential failure point.

00:27:54.439 --> 00:28:00.439
And so being able to do functions that are not necessarily going to work for you, but are going to

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:06.359
And so being able to do functional testing and regression testing easily is crucial.

00:28:07.119 --> 00:28:15.000
And microservices and APIs being a very fundamental thing to the web, there's a lot of supporting

00:28:15.599 --> 00:28:18.160
documentation and software that will help you do this.

00:28:18.760 --> 00:28:21.439
I showed Postman earlier today.

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:24.880
Postman is what we used for every single one of our endpoints.

00:28:24.920 --> 00:28:32.959
Every endpoint that we developed, we, during our pull requests, reviewed the test as well, made sure

00:28:32.959 --> 00:28:39.479
we had adequate testing, adequate coverage, and made sure that it was working when it was supposed

00:28:39.479 --> 00:28:45.280
to work and then caused forced failures when we were supposed to force them.

00:28:47.119 --> 00:28:50.439
Postman is also great for performing schema tests as well.

00:28:50.680 --> 00:28:54.079
That's something that's in a loosely typed language like R or Python.

00:28:54.640 --> 00:29:02.520
It's not very common to check your variable type, or if you do, it kind of clutters up the code.

00:29:03.079 --> 00:29:06.119
Postman can do schema tests as well.

00:29:06.400 --> 00:29:10.359
So you can expect a number when you can test if there's a number when you expect it.

00:29:12.959 --> 00:29:18.160
And finally, the last point here, I don't have a slide on, but the point being is that there's a lot of

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:23.680
research out there, and even you attending this meetup today is a step in this direction, filling in

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:26.800
the knowledge gaps and considering the costs and benefits.

00:29:27.959 --> 00:29:34.839
So I just want to call that out as that's something that if there's some overhead with microservices,

00:29:34.839 --> 00:29:40.319
there's not a lot, and there's multiplicative benefits in the future if you start reusing these

00:29:40.319 --> 00:29:47.400
services. But for each team, it depends on the size of the team, the amount of repeatable work that you

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:50.920
do, as well as the knowledge gaps that you want to overcome.

00:29:53.760 --> 00:30:02.280
So now I'll switch over to a demonstration of the application that we built using microservices.

00:30:03.359 --> 00:30:05.400
This application is called Coda.

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.839
It's the KPMG organization design analyzer.

00:30:09.719 --> 00:30:11.000
Oops, did I choose the wrong one?

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:21.319
So Coda is a tool for users to be able to analyze a company's census, so the entire organization structure.

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:27.359
There are a couple of views of the organization that we provide and some statistics as well.

00:30:27.839 --> 00:30:30.400
The intent is that you can do a quick analysis if you need to.

00:30:31.119 --> 00:30:38.640
You can reorganize the organization if you see people that are in finance reporting to people in sales that may not be so efficient for your organization.

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:50.760
The intent of Coda is to be able to assess, organize, redesign, do some quick analysis or comparisons of your design, and then finally be able to ship to your customer.

00:30:51.719 --> 00:30:56.239
So what I'm showing here is actually the reason that we switched into a React-based front end.

00:30:56.319 --> 00:30:58.959
This is what we call a radio plot.

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:07.040
And this is an organization where, in this case, the CEO is in the center of the org, and the rest of the team is in the back end.

00:31:07.040 --> 00:31:14.280
So the CEO is in the center of the org, and then their direct reportees are the next layer out, and then the reportees outside of that.

00:31:16.479 --> 00:31:28.160
Doing this in Shiny became quite cumbersome, and we'll talk about that in a little bit, because you're working with two languages that are kind of speaking interchangeably within the one language.

00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:42.239
But Coda allows you to do things like, for example, if I wanted to select this person and reassign them here, I could reassign their entire organization, everybody underneath them here as well.

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:46.959
I can just do some simple things like reorder these dots around.

00:31:47.880 --> 00:32:00.439
And I can do things like, I won't run them here, but we can create cuts of the same visual and produce any number of charts, because generally our clients do ask for PowerPoints.

00:32:02.680 --> 00:32:04.760
Again, this is an analysis tool.

00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:15.920
So R&D is colored over here. We see that this person seems to be the lead of R&D, but there are also some people who are in the lead of R&D.

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:23.359
So we can see that this person is the lead of R&D, and we can see that this person is the lead of R&D.

00:32:23.959 --> 00:32:43.760
Well, I can actually click on it. So R&D is colored over here. We see that this person seems to be the lead of R&D, but there are also some people over here that maybe they shouldn't be managing, or maybe we need to separate that into another person, because it's such a wide span of people.

00:32:47.439 --> 00:32:51.199
I won't go into the details of every one of the features. There's some comparison

00:32:52.199 --> 00:33:05.800
abilities as well. And then also just a relatively simple dashboard that shows your organization at different levels, broken up by the departments that are at each level. I didn't upload any compensation data, so it's not here.

00:33:08.280 --> 00:33:14.680
Now if I go over to the implementation side. So this is where users start to make changes to the organization itself.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:15.280
And so,

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:25.839
again, same organization, same CEO. If I wanted to, let's say I want to search for a certain person. Let's do Ferguson Page.

00:33:27.719 --> 00:33:31.680
I would find her, which would be over here.

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:40.079
If I wanted to reassign them, I could move them to this person here. And so now I've kind of modified the organization.

00:33:43.079 --> 00:33:48.680
Also can add in new people to the org by clicking here.

00:33:49.680 --> 00:33:59.680
And one of the features that I personally love is the fact that you can actually track all the history that you're doing here and roll it back. If I made a mistake here, I can remove that.

00:34:01.680 --> 00:34:02.680
The

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:14.679
Coda application started as a shiny app. We were embedding D3 visuals, especially the radial chart inside of the application. We actually had an instance of this as well that I think was really JavaScript, not necessarily D3.

00:34:15.679 --> 00:34:19.679
But those two things, we started getting into the habit of writing code.

00:34:20.679 --> 00:34:28.679
If a user clicked on this node, if a user clicked on a node here, what was the piece of information that they were looking for?

00:34:29.679 --> 00:34:31.679
And so we started to figure out how to do that.

00:34:32.679 --> 00:34:50.679
JavaScript messages from the back end to the front end to trigger a callback to see if a user clicked on this node, if a user clicked on a node here, what was the piece of information that they were looking for?

00:34:51.679 --> 00:34:58.679
So we were data scientists writing in R, writing in JavaScript to get this all to work.

00:34:58.679 --> 00:35:08.679
And so that's why we transitioned over to have React developers write this in JavaScript and D3, but communicate to them using the language that we know, which is R.

00:35:10.679 --> 00:35:14.679
That was the genesis of Coda and why we made this big switch.

00:35:15.679 --> 00:35:19.679
On top of that, the styling and everything was much easier to do.

00:35:21.679 --> 00:35:22.679
In a framework like that.

00:35:24.679 --> 00:35:27.679
The four screens that I'm showing here, I touched on the assess and design.

00:35:28.679 --> 00:35:31.679
So the radial chart and the design of an organization.

00:35:32.679 --> 00:35:45.679
I didn't go into the compare the percent just for time's sake, but the idea here or the intent to show this is that any of the visuals that we have, we have people with the right skill sets doing this.

00:35:46.679 --> 00:35:53.679
And the people like the data scientists working within their own professional areas as well.

00:35:54.679 --> 00:36:01.679
It makes for that kind of separation of duties makes for a lot faster development because you don't have a data scientist learning how to write JavaScript.

00:36:04.679 --> 00:36:10.679
And then just a very basic kind of application level diagram of the application I just showed Coda.

00:36:10.679 --> 00:36:20.679
So very similar to the simple demo that I shared earlier, we have a React web app, but we also have a Power BI dashboard that interacts with our microservice.

00:36:21.679 --> 00:36:24.679
So I mentioned earlier that microservices could be reused.

00:36:25.679 --> 00:36:26.679
This is a perfect example of that.

00:36:27.679 --> 00:36:31.679
Power BI is interacting with the same microservice that our React app is.

00:36:32.679 --> 00:36:42.679
And so now we have two interfaces and one that is quick to, we now have the opportunity to say, okay, well, we want to build this in React because we need high interactivity.

00:36:43.679 --> 00:36:47.679
We want to build this in Power BI because maybe we want to ship that out to the client as a dashboard.

00:36:48.679 --> 00:36:54.679
And so now we give us the freedom to use the best tool for the right problem or for the problem.

00:36:55.679 --> 00:36:57.679
I mentioned sidecars earlier.

00:36:57.679 --> 00:37:02.679
Similarly, in our application, we use that for logging some user authentication and for monitoring.

00:37:03.679 --> 00:37:13.679
And on top of that, one additional kind of major benefit is being able to test the endpoints either in a production server or in a staging server.

00:37:14.679 --> 00:37:15.679
And we do that.

00:37:15.679 --> 00:37:16.679
We do that regularly.

00:37:16.679 --> 00:37:21.679
So every single release that we do, we test the entire app, the entire set of services.

00:37:22.679 --> 00:37:24.679
And we do them periodically as well.

00:37:25.679 --> 00:37:36.679
Netflix actually has an idea of a chaos monkey, which is a testing node, but a testing node designed to try to find weaknesses in your system.

00:37:37.679 --> 00:37:38.679
That's something on our horizon as well.

00:37:39.679 --> 00:37:48.679
The benefit of using microservices is that you can hit what your user would also hit or a copy of that, maybe not.

00:37:48.679 --> 00:37:49.679
Maybe not use the production version.

00:37:52.679 --> 00:37:55.679
And I'll step over this just very quickly.

00:37:56.679 --> 00:38:02.679
But this is our just to connect it back to the design domain driven design.

00:38:03.679 --> 00:38:07.679
So these are the entities and the relationships that we have for our code application.

00:38:08.679 --> 00:38:09.679
And we'll get into the details of that.

00:38:10.679 --> 00:38:14.679
But this is what we started with and gradually built to where we are today.

00:38:15.679 --> 00:38:18.679
So switching into now a recap.

00:38:20.679 --> 00:38:21.679
Tom, would you like to take this one?

00:38:22.679 --> 00:38:22.679


00:38:23.679 --> 00:38:33.679
So going back to what we showed earlier, what is that tradeoff between complexity on users needing interactive graphs, which we're trying to do in D3?

00:38:33.679 --> 00:38:42.679
And that was creating a lot of complications, just debugging that to being able to export things into images, into PowerPoint, where you can actually export things.

00:38:43.679 --> 00:38:50.679
Where these new things were coming along and it was creating some discord within the data science because they're needing to learn more.

00:38:51.679 --> 00:38:52.679
And that just that's very taxing.

00:38:53.679 --> 00:38:54.679
That's very tiring.

00:38:55.679 --> 00:39:01.679
So this allows us to have people focus on front end technologies versus the data science piece of it versus the back end piece of it.

00:39:02.679 --> 00:39:07.679
So this is our path where we first deployed in Coda and other applications that we have.

00:39:07.679 --> 00:39:10.679
Coda is the example that we use here, that monolithic Shiny application.

00:39:11.679 --> 00:39:15.679
So it allows us to do a lot more complexity with not trying to hack around that.

00:39:16.679 --> 00:39:20.679
But then we got into JavaScript messaging and then we got into trying to get D3 to work within Shiny.

00:39:21.679 --> 00:39:24.679
And then it felt like we were doing too much hacking around.

00:39:25.679 --> 00:39:30.679
And over time, we knew that that was going to be a risk to the maintaining of the applications themselves.

00:39:31.679 --> 00:39:39.679
So by switching over to microservices back end and React front end, it allowed us to increase the complexity of what the application was asking for.

00:39:40.679 --> 00:39:45.679
But get us out of that danger zone of trying to hack things together to be able to make it work.

00:39:46.679 --> 00:39:47.679
If we can go to the next slide, Bijan.

00:39:48.679 --> 00:39:49.679
Keep it, you're controlling it.

00:39:50.679 --> 00:39:51.679
So we talked about some of the benefits.

00:39:52.679 --> 00:39:57.679
So those benefits is we allowed that division of labor and specialization, bringing people to focus on what they do well.

00:39:58.679 --> 00:40:01.679
To be able to program in more advanced user interface.

00:40:02.679 --> 00:40:05.679
What you saw here running today was all running off of RStudio Connect.

00:40:06.679 --> 00:40:18.679
So I think subjectively, qualitatively, is a very different looking thing than what people typically expect to see running within an R-based, largely an R-based application.

00:40:19.679 --> 00:40:20.679
Has multiple consumption points.

00:40:21.679 --> 00:40:22.679
Developers can hit those APIs.

00:40:23.679 --> 00:40:25.679
Power BI, BI applications can hit those APIs.

00:40:25.679 --> 00:40:27.679
Custom front end applications can.

00:40:28.679 --> 00:40:29.679
Other programs can hit those APIs.

00:40:30.679 --> 00:40:31.679
So people can consume those.

00:40:32.679 --> 00:40:33.679
They're reusable.

00:40:34.679 --> 00:40:36.679
And you're relying on a wider universe of tools and libraries.

00:40:37.679 --> 00:40:38.679
The R ecosystem is amazing.

00:40:39.679 --> 00:40:41.679
There's hexagons everywhere that allow you to show interconnectivity.

00:40:42.679 --> 00:40:45.679
But all those are really trying to wrap in some other technology.

00:40:46.679 --> 00:40:48.679
This allows us to directly reach out to those other technologies.

00:40:49.679 --> 00:40:52.679
So again, avoids that sort of hackish region.

00:40:52.679 --> 00:40:54.679
And as Bijan mentioned, there's a cost benefit there.

00:40:55.679 --> 00:41:00.679
You just need to see, does this make sense or can I rely on the R ecosystem exclusively?

00:41:01.679 --> 00:41:02.679
And also the Python ecosystem.

00:41:03.679 --> 00:41:08.679
It becomes more code agnostic and really allows you to adopt formal DevOps procedures.

00:41:09.679 --> 00:41:12.679
Continuous integration, continuous deployment, code versioning, Git.

00:41:13.679 --> 00:41:15.679
All this is underlying everything that we've talked about today.

00:41:16.679 --> 00:41:18.679
Because you need to be able to do that very well.

00:41:18.679 --> 00:41:21.679
And I know there's a lot of other presentations about how to use version control and all that.

00:41:22.679 --> 00:41:24.679
And those are fantastic things to dive into.

00:41:25.679 --> 00:41:28.679
But Bijan and the team, we've mentioned a number of challenges.

00:41:29.679 --> 00:41:30.679
It does require more planning.

00:41:31.679 --> 00:41:32.679
There's a cost benefit.

00:41:33.679 --> 00:41:34.679
For every project, do we do pure Shiny?

00:41:35.679 --> 00:41:36.679
Do we do this microservices approach?

00:41:37.679 --> 00:41:40.679
Requires the paramount, the strong team coordination.

00:41:41.679 --> 00:41:43.679
So because it's not all in one thing, it's in different pieces.

00:41:44.679 --> 00:41:45.679
You just need to be coordinated on those different pieces.

00:41:45.679 --> 00:41:49.679
I describe it as building a bridge starting from both sides of a river bank.

00:41:50.679 --> 00:41:52.679
You start on both sides and you need to be able to meet in the middle.

00:41:53.679 --> 00:41:55.679
And if you don't, that bridge isn't going to meet in the middle.

00:41:56.679 --> 00:41:57.679
And that's always what this boils down to.

00:41:58.679 --> 00:42:02.679
And so there's a unique risk within those distributed services.

00:42:03.679 --> 00:42:04.679
And additional skills and resources may be required.

00:42:05.679 --> 00:42:06.679
But if you're a growing team, this is kind of the point of it.

00:42:07.679 --> 00:42:11.679
If you're a growing team, you can make hires in front-end development and other specializations

00:42:12.679 --> 00:42:13.679
to allow them to really flourish and focus on that.

00:42:13.679 --> 00:42:17.679
And again, you're looking at industry standard technologies.

