to understand the infrastructure side away from you.

00:53:18.679 --> 00:53:20.679
You publish and you're in a great position.

00:53:23.679 --> 00:53:24.679
That's awesome.

00:53:25.679 --> 00:53:26.679
And I did not set up that question

00:53:27.679 --> 00:53:28.679
or pay you to say that.

00:53:29.679 --> 00:53:30.679
Awesome.

00:53:31.679 --> 00:53:32.679
One other question was,

00:53:33.679 --> 00:53:35.679
are applications built with microservices

00:53:36.679 --> 00:53:37.679
as responsive as those that adopt

00:53:38.679 --> 00:53:39.679
a monolithic architecture,

00:53:40.679 --> 00:53:43.679
or do microservices introduce a lag?

00:53:44.679 --> 00:53:45.679
A very good question.

00:53:46.679 --> 00:53:47.679
One of the benefits of hosting

00:53:48.679 --> 00:53:49.679
within the RStudio Connect environment

00:53:50.679 --> 00:53:51.679
is that there's little latency between those two

00:53:52.679 --> 00:53:53.679
because the APIs and the front end

00:53:54.679 --> 00:53:55.679
are sitting in the same physical location.

00:53:56.679 --> 00:53:57.679
You could have latency introduced

00:53:58.679 --> 00:53:59.679
if you were to have servers sitting over here

00:54:00.679 --> 00:54:01.679
that were hosting APIs

00:54:01.679 --> 00:54:02.679
and then a front end

00:54:03.679 --> 00:54:04.679
that was sitting somewhere else

00:54:05.679 --> 00:54:06.679
because you then have to rely

00:54:07.679 --> 00:54:08.679
on the slowest part of an application,

00:54:09.679 --> 00:54:10.679
which is the network or the internet

00:54:11.679 --> 00:54:12.679
trying to communicate across all of that.

00:54:13.679 --> 00:54:14.679
Right now, yes, absolutely.

00:54:15.679 --> 00:54:16.679
It's just as responsive,

00:54:17.679 --> 00:54:18.679
if not more so because we're not taking

00:54:19.679 --> 00:54:20.679
one set of code, R,

00:54:21.679 --> 00:54:22.679
then using that to write

00:54:23.679 --> 00:54:24.679
in different language,

00:54:25.679 --> 00:54:26.679
usually JavaScript,

00:54:27.679 --> 00:54:28.679
that is then trying to process

00:54:29.679 --> 00:54:30.679
through the browser or the interpreter,

00:54:31.679 --> 00:54:32.679
is it the code?

00:54:33.679 --> 00:54:34.679
Is it something else?

00:54:35.679 --> 00:54:36.679
Is it the server?

00:54:37.679 --> 00:54:38.679
Is it the browser?

00:54:39.679 --> 00:54:40.679
I can't tell you how many times

00:54:41.679 --> 00:54:42.679
we had questions trying to figure out

00:54:43.679 --> 00:54:44.679
when it was just all monolithic,

00:54:45.679 --> 00:54:46.679
what's causing the latency issues?

00:54:47.679 --> 00:54:48.679
Here, it's just been a lot cleaner.

00:54:49.679 --> 00:54:50.679
There's not a lot of latency

00:54:51.679 --> 00:54:52.679
because those two bits

00:54:53.679 --> 00:54:54.679
are sitting right next to each other.

00:54:55.679 --> 00:54:56.679
Then all the bits of code

00:54:57.679 --> 00:54:58.679
are doing exactly what they're supposed to

00:54:59.679 --> 00:55:00.679
and not trying to do seven different things

00:55:01.679 --> 00:55:02.679
at the same time.

00:55:03.679 --> 00:55:04.679
The question was,

00:55:05.679 --> 00:55:06.679
can you show the backend response data

00:55:07.679 --> 00:55:08.679
through developer tools?

00:55:09.679 --> 00:55:10.679
Yeah.

00:55:11.679 --> 00:55:12.679
Let me see.

00:55:13.679 --> 00:55:14.679
Okay.

00:55:15.679 --> 00:55:16.679
I just made the request

00:55:17.679 --> 00:55:18.679
to generate this chart

00:55:19.679 --> 00:55:20.679
behind the screen here.

00:55:21.679 --> 00:55:22.679
This is the exact response

00:55:23.679 --> 00:55:24.679
of the data.

00:55:25.679 --> 00:55:26.679
In my case,

00:55:27.679 --> 00:55:28.679
I just have the manager ID

00:55:29.679 --> 00:55:30.679
and their designation.

00:55:32.679 --> 00:55:35.679
It's just a simple array

00:55:36.679 --> 00:55:37.679
of all manager IDs

00:55:38.679 --> 00:55:39.679
and designations underneath it.

00:55:42.679 --> 00:55:45.679
Nothing too dramatic.

00:55:46.679 --> 00:55:47.679
You can take a look at this one as well.

00:55:48.679 --> 00:55:49.679
This is the metadata

00:55:50.679 --> 00:55:51.679
that would actually pop up

