00:56:24.679 --> 00:56:25.679
Then this one is for the chart

00:56:26.679 --> 00:56:27.679
that we're looking at there.

00:56:28.679 --> 00:56:29.679
I hope that answers the question

00:56:30.679 --> 00:56:31.679
or if there was a follow-up,

00:56:32.679 --> 00:56:33.679
I'm happy to speak to that.

00:56:34.679 --> 00:56:35.679
That's great.

00:56:36.679 --> 00:56:37.679
Thank you.

00:56:38.679 --> 00:56:39.679
I see one last question on Slido.

00:56:40.679 --> 00:56:41.679
Rahul asked,

00:56:42.679 --> 00:56:43.679
can you speak more

00:56:44.679 --> 00:56:45.679
about the logging microservice?

00:56:46.679 --> 00:56:47.679
Did you build it ground up?

00:56:48.679 --> 00:56:49.679
Did you adopt an off-the-shelf package

00:56:50.679 --> 00:56:51.679
or app?

00:56:52.679 --> 00:56:53.679
We use two services.

00:56:54.679 --> 00:56:55.679
One of them is used

00:56:55.679 --> 00:56:56.679
for infrastructure monitoring

00:56:57.679 --> 00:56:58.679
and network monitoring.

00:56:59.679 --> 00:57:00.679
That is an off-the-shelf service.

00:57:01.679 --> 00:57:02.679
For our applications,

00:57:03.679 --> 00:57:04.679
because we're building these

00:57:05.679 --> 00:57:06.679
completely from scratch,

00:57:07.679 --> 00:57:08.679
we use our own service.

00:57:09.679 --> 00:57:10.679
It's a relatively simple

00:57:11.679 --> 00:57:12.679
activity-based logging

00:57:13.679 --> 00:57:14.679
where if an error happens,

00:57:15.679 --> 00:57:16.679
we log that error.

00:57:17.679 --> 00:57:18.679
If a warning happens,

00:57:19.679 --> 00:57:20.679
we log the warning.

00:57:21.679 --> 00:57:22.679
If it's just a simple request,

00:57:23.679 --> 00:57:24.679
it's an information log.

00:57:25.679 --> 00:57:26.679
That's it.

00:57:27.679 --> 00:57:28.679
Awesome.

